post_text:
Gym Guidelines for Home events in the gymnasium:

• Crowds are split
o Away team on North side and Home team on south side
o Concessions available on north side and south side
o Restrooms available down hallways on north side and south side
• Elementary aged students and younger sit with parents.
• Encourage Social distancing and welcome wearing of masks, but not required
• We do ask fans to have correct change at ticket table. $5 for adults and $3 for students. Not required.
• No one allowed on the court following completion of last match. We ask fans to leave premises in a timely manner upon completion

Build Your Base with Beef is a comprehensive sports nutrition program that utilizes beef as its premier protein. It strives to prepare young athletes and their families for a successful sports season. This program provides a toolkit that contains ready-to-use material as well as resources that lead to overall success towards a healthful lifestyle through a collaborative partnership between the South Dakota Beef Industry Council, Sanford Health, and the Sanford Sports Science.

Thank you Mr. Kolousek for helping make this happen for our athletes.

post_text:
Congratulations to Kenzee Schafer for winning the 2020 Congressional Art Competition!
The contest was open to all South Dakota high school art students. Kenzee’s winning piece will be hung in the United States Capitol building for one year. In addition Kenzee has been invited to a reception highlighting her artwork as well as the other winning art pieces from the rest of the 49 states. To help with student travel, Kenzee also earned a flight credit on Southwest airlines so that she could be in attendance for the exhibit opening and ribbon-cutting ceremony. The Congressional Art Competition is sponsored by members of the U.S. House of Representatives. It’s an opportunity to recognize and encourage the artistic talent in the nation, as well as in each congressional district. The South Dakota Arts Council partners with the congressman’s office to carry out this initiative.

We will be continuing the remote learning until May 1st. This is a challenging time and Wessington Springs School District will continue to strive to meet the needs of the students. The survey that is attached below will provide us with the information that we need to provide meals to students.

The meals are free, regardless of economic status. This service doesn't have any economic impact on the district, the reimbursement comes from the Department of Agriculture.

The survey results will allow us to compile a list and prepare delivery schedules. We will make deliveries every Monday for the week's need. If you do not participate in the survey at this time but later realize the need for meals, feel free to contact me at pandi.pittman@k12.sd.us for the update.

Please refer to the following weblink.
https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/BQG7G55

Dr. Pandi Pittman
Superintendent
Wessington Springs School District

Remote learning will continue the week of March 23-27. All activities scheduled have been cancelled or postponed scheduled during that time. The gym and weight room remain closed.
On Monday, March 23 students can return completed work and pick up new work for the week. This will take place from 9:00 am to 12:00 pm at your child’s respective school building.
FREE school lunches and breakfasts are available to all students for the whole week. These meals can also be picked up Monday, March 23 from 9:00 am to 12:00 pm at the elementary lunchroom.
If students and families cannot make it to the school on Monday, March 23 for school materials and school meals, delivery will be available.
We do need an idea of number of school lunches that need to be prepared and also need to know who will need deliveries. Therefore, please complete the survey below.

post_text:
Tuesday, we celebrated our 100th day of school!
In these pictures, the preschoolers are making their snack mix of 100 things by groups of 10, hunting 100 Hershey's Kisses, and blowing out candles on our special treat cookie!

Preschoolers were asked to imagine that they were given $100 that they could spend on ANYTHING they wanted.

Here are their answers :)

Hadley W. -toy unicorn
Jaiddyn T. -dinosaurs
Lawson F. -a Ninja Turtle Cuddly
Liberty M. -a real baby
Jaxon W. -remote control monster truck
Otto Z. -remote control toy truck
Journey J. -a squirt gun to squirt my brother
Etta K. -remote control dinosaur
Devin M. -water
Kaddilac C. -a Spiderman suit with sticky web gloves
so I can climb walls.
Kershaw R. -little juice bottles
Kolt M. -a dinosaur egg to watch it hatch
Holden S. -a nerf gun
Hazel L. -a Pegasus
Caleb C. -a nerf gun
Robert W. -legos
Alice H. -a new backpack
Cara V. -100 farm toys
Lincoln M. -100 real snowmobiles

Families of current 7-10th graders, please join us on Thursday, February 13th at 6:00pm for a 25-minute parent informational meeting!

A tour director will be there to meet you and explain more about this once-in-a-lifetime adventure to Washington, D.C. and Mt. Vernon during the summer of 2021. Contact Ms. Wagner at donna.wagner@k12.sd.us with any questions.

Please consider joining us if you have any interest at all, as there will be FREE pizza! Don't miss out!
